{"title":"Robust Instance Segmentation through Reasoning about Multi-Object Occlusion","domain":"CV","seeds":[{"problem":"Instance segmentation methods that process objects independently produce inconsistent masks under mutual occlusion, and fully supervised pixel annotations are costly. There is a need to jointly model multiple objects and occluders while training with only bounding boxes.","method":"Extend Compositional Networks to a multi-object generative model that includes N object models plus an outlier (occluder) model, with a per-pixel visibility constraint that only one object (or outlier) can be active (∑_n z_i,n = 1). The model produces per-pixel foreground, context, and occlusion likelihood maps and amodal masks, and is trained weakly using bounding-box-based segmentation to learn priors and mixture components. This generalization enables consistent, occlusion-aware instance segmentation from bounding box supervision only."},{"problem":"Per-object, per-pixel feed-forward segmentations often conflict in overlap regions (multiple objects claiming the same pixels), especially under heavy or same-category occlusions, leading to erroneous masks and classifications.","method":"Introduce an Occlusion Reasoning Module (ORM) that operates on the per-object likelihood maps. It detects conflicts where two objects both predict foreground, resolves them via pixel-level competition by assigning each contested pixel to the object with higher foreground likelihood, and then recovers the pairwise occlusion order by comparing the number of reassigned pixels in the conflict set. Using this order, it enforces consistent labeling in overlaps and feeds the corrected occlusion priors back into the CompositionalNet to mask occluded features and recompute class likelihoods, iterating this top-down self-correction to improve both segmentation and classification under occlusion."},{"problem":"Evaluating robustness to occlusion requires precise amodal annotations and controlled, diverse occlusion scenarios, including cases with unknown occluders, which are hard to obtain from human-labeled datasets.","method":"Construct an Occlusion Challenge dataset by superimposing segmented, fully visible KITTI objects onto random backgrounds to create photo-realistic occlusions with pixel-accurate amodal masks. It provides three controlled scenarios: pairwise occlusion (2 objects), complex multi-object occlusion (4 objects with varied inter-occlusions), and mixed occlusions including previously unseen occluder classes. This dataset enables targeted evaluation across occlusion levels and scenarios."}]}
